         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Herbarium ¶ Royal Gardens Kew ¶ April 17 /72 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I have to thank you for two letters since I last wrote — I have already acknowledged to you the receipt of the £100 for the sixth volume...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">72.04.17</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne. </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Herbarium</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Royal Gardens Kew</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">April 17 /72</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have to thank you for two letters since I last wrote — I have already acknowledged to you the receipt of the £100 for the sixth volume<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See G. Bentham to M, 25 January 1872 (in this edition as 72-01-25a).</p>
               </note> and am much obliged for the trouble you have given yourself about it — I have also to thank you for the complete copy of the 7th vol. of your Fragmenta</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have not advanced very rapidly since I last wrote. I have just finished the <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> with linear embryos which I think Muell. Arg.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See J. Müller (1866); for the Australian Tribe, Stenolobeae, see J. Müller (1864a).</p>
               </note> is right in establishing as a distinct Australian tribe though I do not quite agree with him in some of his generic distinctions — still less can I agree with Baillon in considering the flower-head of <name key="Euphorbia">Euphorbia</name> as a single flower whilst that of <name key="Calycopeplus">Calycopeplus</name> as a flowerhead<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See Baillon (1866), p. 320.</p>
               </note> The two genera are closely allied although I think that <name key="Calycopeplus">Calycopeplus</name> (with a second species amongst Drummonds with a still more developped female perianth and no glands to the involucre) may be kept up rather as a genus than as a section. Baillon appears to me also to have rather hastily united or distinguished species from general habit or foliage without always having regard to the floral or fruit characters and some species of Baillon's are the same of<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">as?</p>
               </note> some of Muell. Arg.! which he had not seen — this was to be expected under the circumstances of the two working contemporaneously without intercommunication. I shall endeavour to avoid that in the <name key="Artocarpeae">Artocarpeae</name> by communicating with Bureau who is doing them for the Prodromus<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bureau (1873).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I presume the <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name> will reach to about half the volume. I have on consulting with Dr Hooker determined on deferring the Palms to a later stage in the series and commence Monocotyledons with <name key="Pandaneae">Pandaneae</name> and allies <name key="Aroideae">Aroideae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">This plan was not followed: <name key="Pandaneae">Pandaneae</name> and <name key="Aroideae">Aroideae</name> followed Palmae in Bentham (1863-78), vol .7, while Monocotyledons began with <name key="Hydrocharideae">Hydrocharideae</name> in vol. 6, p. 255. </p>
               </note>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>etc then the apocarpous orders and then those with inferior ovaries <name key="Hydrocharideae">Hydrocharideae</name> — <name key="Scitamineae">Scitamineae</name> — all the above not numerous in Australia so that room will I suppose be left for the whole of the <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> — if not for the whole of the inferior ovary Orders. I shall be glad therefore to have these Orders sent soon as I do not expect to be much away from work this summer</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As soon as I have done the <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> I shall despatch a second box. The bill of lading of the last was sent off to you by the authorities of the Herbarium</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron F. v. Mueller</p>
